<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#871f78">Originally posted by taobob on 09-01-2000 03:11 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">I had actually spoke about green mobs attacking sitting people on the EQ Boards and their response was "The green mobs attack sitting creatures because sitting increases your aggro range to all mobs, and they view a sitting player as vulnerable..."

Camping is something that people just have to deal with because in order to stop camping Verant would have to either drastically change the game mechanics (which they are unable/unwilling to do because of the programs limitations) or find a way to enforce a 'no camping' rule that would only cause more problems/frustrations. I do like the group quest suggestions, and also believe that rare item 'farming' should be controlled (possibly by a level cap or making the drops only occur for specific levels/classes).

I disagree though that you have to camp to get items/loot or that if you don't camp you get crappy gear... I am constantly moving around the continent when I am solo, because it beats sitting to recover health, and I have some decent stuff and pp in the bank... I'd rather travel/explore while the damn health recovers than sit being bored... 

When grouped up however you are almost required to set up 'a camp' to pull towards because having a bunch of people wandering around leads to the group becoming seperated, which in turns leads to wasted time re-grouping... Casters need to sit to recover mana, so setting up a 'camp' is inevitable. This does not mean however that you should constantly stay in one place, or hunt the same things... I formed a group in W Commonlands one time where we hunted wisps until our group was full, then went and hit the Derv camp in that zone for a bit (2 spawns max), moved to the E Commanlands ruins and smashed some undead, then went to N Ro and took out another Derv camp, and then ended in Oasis killing orcs and then crocs...  

As far as Muse's comments about pathing and other bugs removing the fun from the game, I have to agree, but it could also be considered in this way (smile, have fun  :) anyway ): Pathing problems arise from the monsters being less intelligent than players; Popping monsters could have been hiding or using the natural camoflauge of the landscape; Monsters on different floors might actually hear the echo of the battle (or noisy armor boots ringing on the floor) from a distance in a dungeon... hehehe  All depends on how you look at it....   :D




------------------
Blackivar the Cunning
Halfling Rogue
15th Season
Druzzil Ro Server</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
